% @category: Basic Programmability
% @name: The Macro System
% @description: Define your own commands
@cassilda: macro_guide
  ╔══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╗
  ║                               The Macro System                               ║
  ╚══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╝
  
  Hyades has two programmability systems – a macro system aimed at typesetting co-
  nvenience just like the macro system of TeX, and a general  computational system
  (CL) aimed at efficient general purpose computation. This document describes the
  macro  system. For  CL  and the  Subnivean VM,  see the  𝐶𝑜𝑚𝑝𝑢𝑡𝑎𝑡𝑖𝑜𝑛𝑎𝑙 𝐿𝑎𝑚𝑏𝑑𝑎𝑠 &
  𝑆𝑢𝑏𝑛𝑖𝑣𝑒𝑎𝑛 guide.
  
  Think of macros as a smarter version of “search and replace” – if Hyades finds a
  macro call, it will take the call arguments, find the macro  definition, and li-
  terally replace the call site with the full macro body with argument  references
  replaced. Since the macro body itself can call macros, this process is recursive
  until no more macros are found in the  recursively expanded body, and only calls
  that remain are system  primitives. After that the expanded body is processed by
  the normal parsing and rendering pipeline.
  
  𝐕𝐚𝐫𝐢𝐚𝐛𝐥𝐞𝐬
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  A variable is declared with \𝑙𝑒𝑡<x>{value}, and the value is accessed with {x}:
  
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  \let<x>{123}                                                          │
  │ 2:  │  ${x}                                                                  │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
     ╭─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╮
  ╭──┴────────────╮                                                            │
  │ 𝐻𝑦𝑎δες Output │|··························································|│
  ╰──┬────────────╯                                                            │
     │   123                                                                  ░│
     ╰─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╯
  
  Variables are  𝑝𝑜𝑙𝑦𝑚𝑜𝑟𝑝ℎ𝑖𝑐 – they hold either integers or arbitrary rendered co-
  ntent. When used with  numbers they support  arithmetic; when used with  content
  like \𝐵𝑜𝑥𝑒𝑑{abc} they store and recall rendered output:
  
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  \let<mybox>{\Boxed{Hello, World!}}                                    │
  │ 2:  │  ${mybox}                                                              │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
     ╭─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╮
  ╭──┴────────────╮                                                            │
  │ 𝐻𝑦𝑎δες Output │|··························································|│
  ╰──┬────────────╯                                                            │
     │   ╔═══════════════╗                                                    ░│
     │   ║ Hello, World! ║                                                    ░│
     │   ╚═══════════════╝                                                    ░│
     ╰─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╯
  
  When a variable  holds an integer, it can be changed in place with mutating ope-
  rations like \𝑖𝑛𝑐 (increment), or used as input to arithmetic, logic, and compa-
  rison commands. The numeric operations provided by Hyades are:
  
    ● Incrementing:  \𝑖𝑛𝑐<x>
    ● Decrementing:  \𝑑𝑒𝑐<x>
    ● Adding:  \𝑎𝑑𝑑{a,b}
    ● Subtracting:  \𝑠𝑢𝑏{a,b}
    ● Integer division:  \𝑑𝑖𝑣{a,b}
    ● Multiplication:  \𝑚𝑢𝑙{a,b}
    ● Modulo:  \𝑚𝑜𝑑{a,b}
    ● Assignment:  \𝑙𝑒𝑡<y>{\𝑎𝑑𝑑{a,b}}
    ● Equality:  \𝑒𝑞{{x},1}
    ● Non-equality:  \𝑛𝑒{{x},1}
    ● Less Than:  \𝑙𝑡{a,b}
    ● Less Or Equal Than:  \𝑙𝑒{a,b}
    ● Greater Than:  \𝑔𝑡{a,b}
    ● Greater Or Equal Than:  \𝑔𝑒{a,b}
  
  An example:
  
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  \let<x>{123}                                                          │
  │ 2:  │  \inc<x> \\ % 124                                                      │
  │ 3:  │  \inc<x> \\ % 125                                                      │
  │ 4:  │  \div{${x},5} \\ % 25                                                  │
  │ 5:  │  \mul{${x},${x}} \\ % 15625                                            │
  │ 6:  │                                                                        │
  │ 7:  │  \let<y>{\add{${x},${x}}}                                              │
  │ 8:  │                                                                        │
  │ 9:  │  ${y} \\ % 250                                                         │
  │ 10: │  \eq{${x},${y}} \\ 0                                                   │
  │ 11: │  \ne{${x},${y}} \\ 1                                                   │
  │ 12: │  \eq{${x},\sub{${y},${x}}}  \\ 1                                       │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
     ╭─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╮
  ╭──┴────────────╮                                                            │
  │ 𝐻𝑦𝑎δες Output │|··························································|│
  ╰──┬────────────╯                                                            │
     │ 25                                                                     ░│
     │ 15625                                                                  ░│
     │                                                                        ░│
     │ 250                                                                    ░│
     │ 0                                                                      ░│
     │ 1                                                                      ░│
     │ 1                                                                      ░│
     ╰─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╯
  
  𝐒𝐜𝐨𝐩𝐢𝐧𝐠 𝐑𝐮𝐥𝐞𝐬
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  Variables are subject to simple scoping rules:
  
    ● If the IDENTIFIER is all caps, it has a GLOBAL scope:
  
                                 ┌───────────────────┐
                                 │ \let<MYGLOB>{123} │
                                 └───────────────────┘
  
    ● If the identifier is not all caps, it has a local scope:
  
                                 ┌────────────────────┐
                                 │ \let<mylocal>{456} │
                                 └────────────────────┘
  
  
  All  declarations, access, and mutation of a GLOBAL variable will refer to a si-
  ngle storage  location no matter  where and when they’re  invoked; whereas local
  variables refer to one location 𝐏𝐄𝐑 𝐌𝐀𝐂𝐑𝐎 𝐄𝐗𝐏𝐀𝐍𝐒𝐈𝐎𝐍.
  
  Let’s explain this by example – a common use of variables is counting  chapters,
  sections, etc., so let’s build a simple chapter macro that  automatically incre-
  ments chapter numbers. Start with a local variable:
  
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  \let<chapno>{0}                                                       │
  │ 2:  │                                                                        │
  │ 3:  │  \macro<\chapter{title}>{%                                             │
  │ 4:  │      \inc<chapno>                                                      │
  │ 5:  │      \culn[pad:2]{${chapno}.\quad ${title}}                            │
  │ 6:  │  }                                                                     │
  │ 7:  │                                                                        │
  │ 8:  │  \chapter{The Mask}                                                    │
  │ 9:  │  \chapter{The Yellow Sign}                                             │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
     ╭─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╮
  ╭──┴────────────╮                                                            │
  │ 𝐻𝑦𝑎δες Output │|··························································|│
  ╰──┬────────────╯                                                            │
     │                                                                        ░│
     │                                                                        ░│
     │                             1.  The Mask                               ░│
     │                           ────────────────                             ░│
     │                          1.  The Yellow Sign                           ░│
     │                        ───────────────────────                         ░│
     ╰─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╯
  
  In the above example the local variable 𝑐ℎ𝑎𝑝𝑛𝑜 is not accessible to the \𝑐ℎ𝑎𝑝𝑡𝑒𝑟
  macro since the top-level document and each macro expansion use different hygie-
  nization  scope (more on hygienization in advanced topics). The only way for the
  macro to access a local  from a different  hyg. scope is to know its  hygienized
  name. This is achievable by passing the local as reference:
  
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  \macro<\chapterbyref[counter]{title}>{%                               │
  │ 2:  │      \inc<${counter}>                                                  │
  │ 3:  │      \culn[pad:2]{${${counter}}.\quad ${title}}                        │
  │ 4:  │  }                                                                     │
  │ 5:  │                                                                        │
  │ 6:  │  \chapterbyref[counter:\ref<chapno>]{The Mask}                         │
  │ 7:  │  \chapterbyref[counter:\ref<chapno>]{The Yellow Sign}                  │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
     ╭─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╮
  ╭──┴────────────╮                                                            │
  │ 𝐻𝑦𝑎δες Output │|··························································|│
  ╰──┬────────────╯                                                            │
     │                             1.  The Mask                               ░│
     │                           ────────────────                             ░│
     │                          2.  The Yellow Sign                           ░│
     │                        ───────────────────────                         ░│
     ╰─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╯
  
  Here we pass  \𝑟𝑒𝑓{chapno} as an optional  argument. If you just  print out what
  the command produces, it’s something like
  
                                     _m0_chapno
  
  which is the real key to the  underlying storage. Globals don’t undergo hygieni-
  zation, so they are  accessible with the variable names directly. Let’s make use
  of that to write a cleaner chapter macro:
  
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  \let<CHAPNO>{0}                                                       │
  │ 2:  │  \macro<\chapterglobal{title}>{%                                       │
  │ 3:  │      \inc<CHAPNO>                                                      │
  │ 4:  │      \culn[pad:2]{${CHAPNO}.\quad ${title}}                            │
  │ 5:  │  }                                                                     │
  │ 6:  │                                                                        │
  │ 7:  │  % Some text here...                                                   │
  │ 8:  │                                                                        │
  │ 9:  │  \chapterglobal{The Yellow Sign}                                       │
  │ 10: │                                                                        │
  │ 11: │  % Some text here...                                                   │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
     ╭─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╮
  ╭──┴────────────╮                                                            │
  │ 𝐻𝑦𝑎δες Output │|··························································|│
  ╰──┬────────────╯                                                            │
     │                             1.  The Mask                               ░│
     │                           ────────────────                             ░│
     │                                                                        ░│
     │ Although I knew  nothing of chemistry, I listened  fascinated. He pi-  ░│
     │ cked up an Easter lily which  Genevieve had brought that morning from  ░│
     │ Notre Dame, and dropped it into the basin.  Instantly the liquid lost  ░│
     │ its crystalline clearness.                                             ░│
     │                                                                        ░│
     │                          2.  The Yellow Sign                           ░│
     │                        ───────────────────────                         ░│
     │                                                                        ░│
     │ There are so many things which are  impossible to explain! Why should  ░│
     │ certain  chords in music make me think of the brown and  golden tints  ░│
     │ of autumn foliage? Why should the Mass of Sainte Cecile bend my thou-  ░│
     │ ghts  wandering among caverns whose walls blaze with ragged masses of  ░│
     │ virgin silver? What was it in the roar and turmoil of Broadway at six  ░│
     │ o’clock that flashed before my eyes the picture of a still Breton fo-  ░│
     │ rest where  sunlight filtered through spring foliage and Sylvia bent,  ░│
     │ half  curiously, half tenderly, over a small green lizard, murmuring:  ░│
     │ “To think that this also is a little ward of God!“                     ░│
     ╰─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╯
  
  
  𝐂𝐨𝐧𝐝𝐢𝐭𝐢𝐨𝐧𝐚𝐥 𝐄𝐯𝐚𝐥𝐮𝐚𝐭𝐢𝐨𝐧
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  The \𝑖𝑓-\𝑒𝑙𝑠𝑒  construction lets you branch through  multiple paths just like in
  other  programming languages (and TeX). The syntax is a bit different though – I
  didn’t want to feel limited by the TeX grammar.
  
  The syntax is simple:
  
  ┌─────────────────────────────┐
  │ \if{condition}{true branch} │
  └─────────────────────────────┘
  
  And optionally:
  
  ┌────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ \if{condition}{true branch}\else{false branch} │
  └────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
  
  The \𝑐𝑜𝑛𝑑𝑖𝑡𝑖𝑜𝑛 can be anything that evaluates to an integer, where:
  
                                   ⎧  𝐓𝐑𝐔𝐄 iff 𝑐𝑜𝑛𝑑 ∈ ℤ ∖ 0,
                        if(𝑐𝑜𝑛𝑑) = ⎨
                                   ⎩ 𝐅𝐀𝐋𝐒𝐄 iff 𝑐𝑜𝑛𝑑 = 0.
  
  As an example,  let’s write a simple  automatic grader that  turns a name  and a
  score into a row that also contains a calculated grade.
  
  The grader macro:
  
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  \macro<\grade[name]{score}>{                                          │
  │ 2:  │      \row[frame:{b:single}]{                                           │
  │ 3:  │          \col{${name}}                                                 │
  │ 4:  │          \col{${score}}                                                │
  │ 5:  │          \col{\if{\ge{${score},90}}{%                                  │
  │ 6:  │                      A%                                                │
  │ 7:  │                  }\else{%                                              │
  │ 8:  │                      \if{\ge{${score},80}}{%                           │
  │ 9:  │                          B%                                            │
  │ 10: │                      }\else{F}%                                        │
  │ 11: │                  }                                                     │
  │ 12: │              }                                                         │
  │ 13: │      }                                                                 │
  │ 14: │  }                                                                     │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
  
  We can then use it to generate table rows like so:
  
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  \center{                                                              │
  │ 2:  │  \table[width:20,pad:{l:1,r:1},frame:none]{                            │
  │ 3:  │      \row[frame:{b:double}]{                                           │
  │ 4:  │          \col[align:r]{Student}                                        │
  │ 5:  │          \col[width:5,align:c]{\textpercent}                           │
  │ 6:  │          \col[width:3,align:c]{}                                       │
  │ 7:  │      }                                                                 │
  │ 8:  │      \grade[Knuth D.]{100}                                             │
  │ 9:  │      \grade[Olsak P.]{89}                                              │
  │ 10: │      \grade[Gates W.]{3}                                               │
  │ 11: │  }}                                                                    │
  │ 12: │                                                                        │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
     ╭─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╮
  ╭──┴────────────╮                                                            │
  │ 𝐻𝑦𝑎δες Output │|··························································|│
  ╰──┬────────────╯                                                            │
     │                             Student   %                                ░│
     │                         ════════════════════                           ░│
     │                            Knuth D.  100  A                            ░│
     │                         ────────────────────                           ░│
     │                            Olsak P.  89   B                            ░│
     │                         ────────────────────                           ░│
     │                            Gates W.   3   F                            ░│
     ╰─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╯
  
  (The  content of the  table is a little  nod to RNDr. Petr  Olšák, my university
  algebra teacher who unknowingly got me into TeX.)
  
  Note that the \𝑒𝑙𝑠𝑒 branch, if present, must occur 𝑖𝑚𝑚𝑒𝑑𝑖𝑎𝑡𝑒𝑙𝑦 after the closing
  bracket of the \𝑖𝑓  branch, because we lack an “end”  command. If the  \𝑒𝑙𝑠𝑒 co-
  mmand doesn’t follow  immediately, the conditional  statement is fully completed
  and any further \𝑒𝑙𝑠𝑒 won’t be executed.
  
  
  𝐌𝐞𝐚𝐬𝐮𝐫𝐞/𝐑𝐞𝐜𝐚𝐥𝐥 𝐒𝐲𝐬𝐭𝐞𝐦
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  The Measure/Recall System provides two key capabilities:
  
    ● Capture content for further re-use
    ● Measure the content for dynamic layout purposes
  
  The \𝑚𝑒𝑎𝑠𝑢𝑟𝑒 command measures the dimensions of the output rendered by its argu-
  ment. It also stores the  argument so it can be recalled later. Here is the full
  pipeline:
  
    ● First, the content is virtually rendered in an infinite space, where it is
      measured
    ● Then, the content is stored in the content registry
    ● Three keys are returned to the user:
      ○ 1 key for the stored content, with which it can be recalled
      ○ 2 variable keys – the width and the height
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  \measure<c,w,h>{$\frac{\alpha}{\beta}+\gamma$}                        │
  │ 2:  │                                                                        │
  │ 3:  │  \fancylist{                                                           │
  │ 4:  │      - width: ${w}                                                     │
  │ 5:  │      - height: ${h}                                                    │
  │ 6:  │  }                                                                     │
  │ 7:  │                                                                        │
  │ 8:  │  Content: ${c}                                                         │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
     ╭─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╮
  ╭──┴────────────╮                                                            │
  │ 𝐻𝑦𝑎δες Output │|··························································|│
  ╰──┬────────────╯                                                            │
     │ ● width: 7                                                             ░│
     │ ● height: 3                                                            ░│
     │                                                                        ░│
     │           α                                                            ░│
     │ Content: ─── + γ                                                       ░│
     │           β                                                            ░│
     ╰─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╯
  
  This vastly increases the power of macros, which can do things like:
  
    ● Fit stuff snugly into boxes
    ● Render underlines that scale with the text they underline
    ● Make responsive tabular layouts
    ● Render code listings
  
  ┌────┐┌──────┐┌──┐┌────┐┌──┐┌───┐┌───────────┐┌──────┐┌─────┐
  │This││system││is││used││by││the││\𝑡𝑖𝑔ℎ𝑡𝑓𝑟𝑎𝑚𝑒││𝑠𝑡𝑑𝑙𝑖𝑏││macro│
  └────┘└──────┘└──┘└────┘└──┘└───┘└───────────┘└──────┘└─────┘
  In fact the Measure/Recall system was first designed just to support this macro.
  
            ............................................................
                              A SIMPLE UNDERLINE MACRO
  
            Here’s an example of a simple  underline macro, which measu-
            res the  content passed to it, then  renders the content ce-
            ntered,  and  renders a centered  horizontal  rule  under it
            using the measured width.
  
              1:  │  \macro<\myunderline{content}>{%
              2:  │      \measure<c,w,h>{${content}}
              3:  │      \center{%
              4:  │          ${c}\\
              5:  │          \center{\hrule[${w}]}
              6:  │      }
              7:  │  }
              8:  │  
              9:  │  \myunderline{Hey, this is underlined}
  
            Many   different   underline   macros   are   available   in
            𝐻𝑦𝑎δες::stdlib – feel free to explore it and create your own
            personal   library.   You’re   even   encouraged  to  extend
            𝐻𝑦𝑎δες::stdlib and make a pull request to the repo!
            ............................................................
  
  
  𝐂𝐨𝐧𝐭𝐞𝐧𝐭 𝐒𝐭𝐨𝐫𝐚𝐠𝐞
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  We saw that  variables can hold  rendered content. For  content that you want to
  store and recall multiple times, \𝑙𝑒𝑡 is the primary way:
  
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  \let<mybox>{%                                                         │
  │ 2:  │      \center{\Tightframe{This is my box.}}%                            │
  │ 3:  │  }                                                                     │
  │ 4:  │                                                                        │
  │ 5:  │  % Render it twice                                                     │
  │ 6:  │  ${mybox}                                                              │
  │ 7:  │  ${mybox}                                                              │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
     ╭─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╮
  ╭──┴────────────╮                                                            │
  │ 𝐻𝑦𝑎δες Output │|··························································|│
  ╰──┬────────────╯                                                            │
     │                          ╔═════════════════╗                           ░│
     │                          ║ This is my box. ║                           ░│
     │                          ╚═════════════════╝                           ░│
     │                          ╔═════════════════╗                           ░│
     │                          ║ This is my box. ║                           ░│
     │                          ╚═════════════════╝                           ░│
     ╰─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╯
  
            ............................................................
                               LEGACY: ASSIGN/RECALL
  
            The  \𝑎𝑠𝑠𝑖𝑔𝑛/\𝑟𝑒𝑐𝑎𝑙𝑙 pair is the  original way to store  and
            recall  content. It still  works and  you’ll see it in older
            code:
  
              1:  │  \assign<mybox>{\center{\Tightframe{stored}}}
              2:  │  \recall<mybox>
  
            For new code, prefer  \𝑙𝑒𝑡<name>{content} and ${name}, which
            work uniformly for both integers and content.
            ............................................................
  
  
  𝐌𝐀𝐂𝐑𝐎𝐒
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  Macros are the primary text-processing programmability feature in 𝐻𝑦𝑎δες. As de-
  scribed in the  introduction, they are a smart recursive  find-replace – “smart”
  because they create their own variable scopes. Not everything prefixed with \ is
  a macro though, as there are several clades of \:
  
    ● Command
      ○ A 𝐻𝑦𝑎δες kernel function whose execution and rendering are entirely
        defined in C. Some examples:
        ○ \𝑚𝑎𝑐𝑟𝑜
        ○ \𝑠𝑞𝑟𝑡
        ○ \𝑡𝑒𝑥𝑡𝑖𝑡
    ● System Macro
      ○ Is a macro that is 𝑡𝑟𝑎𝑛𝑠𝑙𝑎𝑡𝑒𝑑 by the 𝐻𝑦𝑎δες kernel to a macro that is then
        processed by the standard macro pipeline just like any other macro
      ○ This is required to handle syntax that the standard macro pipeline cannot
        parse. Some examples:
        ○ \𝑙𝑖𝑠𝑡 is a system macro, because it uses a Markdown syntax to define the
          level of nesting of list items. Even though 𝐻𝑦𝑎δες does have string
          processing primitives, lists require more powerful parsing than 𝐻𝑦𝑎δες
          offers.
        ○ \𝑡𝑎𝑏𝑙𝑒 is another example
    ● 𝐻𝑦𝑎δες::stdlib Macro
      ○ Macros written in 𝐻𝑦𝑎δες itself (not C) that ship with 𝐻𝑦𝑎δες by default.
        In practice, these live in the git repo in a big cassilda file
        ([stdlib.cld]), and during the build this file is used to generate C
        source where these macros exist as strings in a system macro registry.
        Some examples:
        ○ \𝑓𝑎𝑛𝑐𝑦𝑙𝑖𝑠𝑡𝑖𝑛𝑔 uses a 𝑙𝑖𝑛𝑒 𝑟𝑜𝑢𝑡𝑖𝑛𝑒 to wrap content in a box with a line
          number gutter
        ○ \𝑐𝑒𝑛𝑡𝑒𝑟, \ℎ𝑐𝑒𝑛𝑡𝑒𝑟, \𝑡𝑖𝑔ℎ𝑡𝑓𝑟𝑎𝑚𝑒, …
    ● User Macro
      ○ Macros defined by the user
      ○ Users can build their macro libraries and then \𝑖𝑛𝑝𝑢𝑡 them into their
        documents and use them, or they can of course define them right in the
        document
  
  Let’s take a look now at how the system macro \𝑙𝑖𝑠𝑡 is expanded by the kernel:
  
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  \diagnostics{expansion}                                               │
  │ 2:  │  \diag_expand{                                                         │
  │ 3:  │      \list{                                                            │
  │ 4:  │          - First row                                                   │
  │ 5:  │          - Nested row                                                  │
  │ 6:  │          - Top-level again                                             │
  │ 7:  │      }                                                                 │
  │ 8:  │  }                                                                     │
  │ 9:  │  \printdiagnostics                                                     │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
     ╭─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╮
  ╭──┴────────────╮                                                            │
  │ 𝐻𝑦𝑎δες Output │|··························································|│
  ╰──┬────────────╯                                                            │
     │ \begin{vbox}                                                           ░│
     │     \child{                                                            ░│
     │         \begin{hbox}                                                   ░│
     │         \child[1]{-}                                                   ░│
     │         \child[1]{}                                                    ░│
     │         \child[auto]{                                                  ░│
     │             \linebreaker{raggedright}                                  ░│
     │             First row                                                  ░│
     │             \linebreaker{greedy}                                       ░│
     │         }                                                              ░│
     │         \end{hbox}                                                     ░│
     │     }                                                                  ░│
     │     \child{                                                            ░│
     │         \begin{hbox}                                                   ░│
     │         \child[2]{}                                                    ░│
     │         \child[1]{-}                                                   ░│
     │         \child[1]{}                                                    ░│
     │         \child[auto]{                                                  ░│
     │             \linebreaker{raggedright}                                  ░│
     │             Nested row                                                 ░│
     │             \linebreaker{greedy}                                       ░│
     │         }                                                              ░│
     │         \end{hbox}                                                     ░│
     │     }                                                                  ░│
     │     \child{                                                            ░│
     │         \begin{hbox}                                                   ░│
     │         \child[1]{-}                                                   ░│
     │         \child[1]{}                                                    ░│
     │         \child[auto]{                                                  ░│
     │             \linebreaker{raggedright}                                  ░│
     │             Top-level again                                            ░│
     │             \linebreaker{greedy}                                       ░│
     │         }                                                              ░│
     │         \end{hbox}                                                     ░│
     │     }                                                                  ░│
     │ \end{vbox}                                                             ░│
     ╰─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╯
  
  You can use the 𝐻𝑦𝑎δες  diagnostic commands to inspect how any source looks when
  it is expanded. The \𝑙𝑖𝑠𝑡 system macro above is expanded to layout primitives:
  
    ● 3 vertically stacked children (vbox)
    ● Each child:
      ○ Is a horizontal stack (hbox)
      ○ Fixed-size empty child to render the level indent
      ○ 1-char-sized child to render the bullet
      ○ Autosized last child to render the line content using the remaining width
        ○ Content rendered ragged right (typographical term for left justification
          – since the content is not justified on both sides, the lack of space
          distribution on the lines makes the right edge of the paragraph appear
          ragged)
        ○ Linebreaker is reset to its original value
  
  That was the \𝑙𝑖𝑠𝑡  system macro. The  \𝑓𝑎𝑛𝑐𝑦𝑙𝑖𝑠𝑡 macro that is used  throughout
  this  document is, however, a ::stdlib  macro – a thin wrapper around \𝑙𝑖𝑠𝑡 that
  customizes the bullet point appearance based on the rendering mode:
  
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  \macro<\fancylist[indent=2]{content}>{                                │
  │ 2:  │    \assign<uni>{%                                                      │
  │ 3:  │      \list[indent:${indent}, point1:●, point2:○, point3:○, ragged:1]%  │
  │ 4:  │        {${content}}}                                                   │
  │ 5:  │                                                                        │
  │ 6:  │    \assign<asc>{%                                                      │
  │ 7:  │      \list[indent:${indent}, point1:-, point2:-, point3:-, ragged:1]%  │
  │ 8:  │        {${content}}}                                                   │
  │ 9:  │                                                                        │
  │ 10: │    \if{\unicode}{\recall<uni>}\else{\recall<asc>}                      │
  │ 11: │  }                                                                     │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
  
  The  \𝑢𝑛𝑖𝑐𝑜𝑑𝑒 command returns 0 if the  content is being  rendered in the  ASCII
  mode (which is done by \𝑠𝑒𝑡𝑢𝑛𝑖𝑐𝑜𝑑𝑒{false})  and 1 otherwise. The macro creates a
  content  variable for both cases and then  decides which one to recall. The uni-
  code mode allows us to render nicer bullet points. It’s a good  practice to take
  \𝑢𝑛𝑖𝑐𝑜𝑑𝑒 into account in macros when they  potentially render non-ASCII  output.
  During  development I often wasn’t  disciplined enough to maintain this practice
  everywhere, so you might find math that  produces unicode in either mode – some-
  thing I’m actively fixing.
  
                                     Declaring
                                   o═══════════o
  
  Let’s learn how to write macros. A macro must start with the \𝑚𝑎𝑐𝑟𝑜 command, fo-
  llowed by a meta-argument (denoted by angle brackets) containing the signature –
  basically a prescription of how the  macro can be called. The meta  brackets are
  followed by curly brackets with the macro body:
  
                ┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
                │ \macro<\boosty[state=sleeping, indent]{text}>{% │
                │     % we'll put the macro body here             │
                │ }                                               │
                └─────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
  
  This signature tells you:
  
      ● The macro is called “boosty”
      ● There are two optional parameters:
        ○ state: has a default string value “sleeping”
        ○ indent: has a default value of nothing
        ○ In general there can be 0 - N optional parameters
      ● There is one primary (required) parameter “text”
        ○ We can have more 1 - N such parameters
      ● We cannot define meta parameters
  
                               WHAT’S WITH THE % SIGN?
  
  All parameters can be accessed within the body using
  
                                  ┌──────────────┐
                                  │ ${paramname} │
                                  └──────────────┘
  
  Let’s add some body to our macro:
  
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  \macro<\boosty[state=sleeping, indent]{text}>{%                       │
  │ 2:  │      \assign<sleeping>{\verb#                                          │
  │ 3:  │    |\      _,,,---,,_                                                  │
  │ 4:  │    /,`.-'`'    -.  ;-;;,_                                              │
  │ 5:  │   |,4-  ) )-,_. ,\ (  `'-'                                             │
  │ 6:  │  '---''(_/--'  `-'\_)#}                                                │
  │ 7:  │      \assign<awake>{\verb#                                             │
  │ 8:  │  _                ___       _.--.                                      │
  │ 9:  │  \`.|\..----...-'`   `-._.-'_.-'`                                      │
  │ 10: │  /  ' `         ,       __.--'                                         │
  │ 11: │  )/' _/     \   `-_,   /                                               │
  │ 12: │  `-'" `"\_  ,_.-;_.-\_ ',                                              │
  │ 13: │      _.-'_./   {_.'   ; /                                              │
  │ 14: │     {_.-``-'         {_/#}                                             │
  │ 15: │                                                                        │
  │ 16: │      \measureref<\ref<x>,\ref<width>,\ref<height>,\ref<awake>>         │
  │ 17: │      \assign<textbox>{\frame[${width}]{${text}}}                       │
  │ 18: │                                                                        │
  │ 19: │      \let<is_sleeping>{\streq{${state},sleeping}}                      │
  │ 20: │      \let<is_awake>{\streq{${state},awake}}                            │
  │ 21: │      \let<known_state>{                                                │
  │ 22: │          \add{% = OR                                                   │
  │ 23: │              ${is_sleeping},                                           │
  │ 24: │              ${is_awake}}                                              │
  │ 25: │      }                                                                 │
  │ 26: │                                                                        │
  │ 27: │      \if{${known_state}}{%                                             │
  │ 28: │          ${${state}} \\                                                │
  │ 29: │          ${textbox}                                                    │
  │ 30: │      }\else{%                                                          │
  │ 31: │          $                                                             │
  │ 32: │          \text{Error: Boosty only has 2 states: }                      │
  │ 33: │          \cases{                                                       │
  │ 34: │              \text{sleeping} \\                                        │
  │ 35: │              \text{awake}                                              │
  │ 36: │          }                                                             │
  │ 37: │          $                                                             │
  │ 38: │      }                                                                 │
  │ 39: │  }                                                                     │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
  
  This macro also lives in ::stdlib as \𝑏𝑜𝑜𝑠𝑡𝑦, as a tribute to my cat, whose name
  is Boosty. :) By defining it again in our document, we override the ::stdlib ma-
  cro. Let’s unpack what it’s doing:
  
      ● \𝑎𝑠𝑠𝑖𝑔𝑛
        ○ We define a content variable “sleeping” and we assign to it an ASCII art
          of a sleeping cat.
          ○ \𝑣𝑒𝑟𝑏 starts a 𝑣𝑒𝑟𝑏𝑎𝑡𝑖𝑚 𝑒𝑛𝑣𝑖𝑟𝑜𝑛𝑚𝑒𝑛𝑡, which, just like in TeX, will
            render the enclosed text verbatim (no processing whatsoever) until the
            first occurrence of the terminating character that immediately follows
            the command (in our case it’s “#“ – terminating character may be any
            non-letter character that doesn’t occur in the verbatim content. The
            usual pick is “|“, but our ASCII art already uses that).
        ○ Similarly we define an awake cat.
      ● \𝑚𝑒𝑎𝑠𝑢𝑟𝑒
        ○ We \𝑚𝑒𝑎𝑠𝑢𝑟𝑒 the width of the wider cat
          ○ \𝑚𝑒𝑎𝑠𝑢𝑟𝑒𝑟𝑒𝑓 is a variant of \𝑚𝑒𝑎𝑠𝑢𝑟𝑒 which does not expand its
            arguments like \𝑚𝑒𝑎𝑠𝑢𝑟𝑒, but instead accepts hygienized registry
            references (\𝑟𝑒𝑓) and works directly on the registries, circumventing
            the standard pipeline. This exists mainly because of \𝑣𝑒𝑟𝑏, which has
            a very complicated path through the standard pipeline and can
            sometimes produce non-obvious results when combined with other
            advanced features.
        ○ We create a content variable called “textbox”, to which we assign the
          text that was passed in, and decorate it with a frame exactly the width
          we calculated above.
          ○ \𝑓𝑟𝑎𝑚𝑒 is a foundational framing macro that accepts many arguments,
            but here we only use it in its default form, which renders a
            single-line frame with sharp contents.
      ● Parse parameters
        ○ We define two variables (is_sleeping and is_awake)
          ○ We initialize them with 0 or 1 based on whether the “state” parameter
            matches “sleeping” or “awake” via \𝑠𝑡𝑟𝑒𝑞
          ○ Strings are passed without any special delimiters, because there is
            really no such thing as the string type in the macro system of 𝐻𝑦𝑎δες
            – whatever value you pass in will just be physically placed wherever
            it is referred to with ${value}.
        ○ We define a helper variable called “known_state”
          ○ We assign to it the arithmetic analogy of the logical OR:
          ○ Addition
          ○ 0 + 0 = 0 (false)
          ○ 0 + 1 = 1 (true)
          ○ 1 + 0 = 1 (true)
          ○ 1 + 1 = 1 (true)
      ● Rendering
        ○ If the state is known (i.e. either “sleeping” or “awake” – strings that
          directly match the names of the content variables that we defined
          earlier), we will use indirection (${${x}}), fetch and render the
          associated ASCII art.
        ○ If it is not known, we will render an error message.
  
            ............................................................
            ┌─────────────────────────────┬────────────────────────────┐
            │      Logical Operator       │   Arithmetic Equivalent    │
            ├─────────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────┤
            │       𝑥 ∨ 𝑦 (𝑥 OR 𝑦)        │           𝑥 + 𝑦            │
            ├─────────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────┤
            │       𝑥 ∧ 𝑦 (𝑥 AND 𝑦)       │           𝑥 ⋅ 𝑦            │
            ├─────────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────┤
            │         ¬𝑥 (NOT 𝑥)          │           1 − 𝑥            │
            ├─────────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────┤
            │       𝑥 ⊕ 𝑦 (𝑥 XOR 𝑦)       │        𝑥 + 𝑦 mod 2         │
            └─────────────────────────────┴────────────────────────────┘
            ............................................................
  
                                      Calling
                                    o═════════o
  
  A macro is called the same way it is defined. Optional  arguments use named fie-
  lds by default; positional syntax is not supported. Here are some calling conve-
  ntions:
  
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  $\eval[to:2,from:1]{(x)}$ % Order doesn't matter.                     │
  │ 2:  │  $\eval[1, 2]{(x)}$ % DOES NOT WORK!                                   │
  │ 3:  │                                                                        │
  │ 4:  │  \columns[4]{left}{right}                                              │
  │ 5:  │  \columns[pad:4]{left}{right}                                          │
  │ 6:  │  \columns[pad=4]{left}{right} % Alternative syntax                     │
  │ 7:  │  \columns{left}{right} % Default employed                              │
  │ 8:  │                                                                        │
  │ 9:  │  % Structured syntax for optional arguments                            │
  │ 10: │  \concatadd[x:{a:4,b:3},y:{a:5,b:6}]                                   │
  │ 11: │  \concatadd[x:{a:4,b:3}]                                               │
  │ 12: │  \concatadd                                                            │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
  
  
  
            ............................................................
            Any macro may be invoked using the LaTeX  environment conve-
            ntion. Internally it is translated to a standard TeX call.
  
              1:  │  \begin{center}
              2:  │      Centered content
              3:  │      $$ c^2 = a^2 + b^2 $$
              4:  │  \end{center}
  
            This is true  for any user  macro, system macro,  and Hyades
            command with the exception of \𝑏𝑒𝑔𝑖𝑛{hbox/vbox},  which is a
            layout  primitive that exists in the  environment form nati-
            vely and will not be translated to the TeX form.
            ............................................................
  
  
  
                                   Line Routines
                                 o═══════════════o
  
  Line routines are an advanced feature inspired by TeX’s output  routines, except
  they work with lines, not pages. They allow you to post-process a rendered  line
  using the full 𝐻𝑦𝑎δες  typesetting arsenal. Line  routines were designed  mainly
  for the code \𝑙𝑖𝑠𝑡𝑖𝑛𝑔 and \𝑓𝑎𝑛𝑐𝑦𝑙𝑖𝑠𝑡𝑖𝑛𝑔 macros, allowing you to post-process ve-
  rbatim content, frame it, and add a line number gutter. Let’s look at the macro:
  
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  \macro<\fancylisting{c}>{                                             │
  │ 2:  │      \titleframe[pad:0]{\lineroutine<numbering>{${c}}}                 │
  │ 3:  │  }                                                                     │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
  
  A line routine is invoked by calling \𝑙𝑖𝑛𝑒𝑟𝑜𝑢𝑡𝑖𝑛𝑒<r>{content}. The command expe-
  cts content in its required  parameter, and a macro with a specific signature in
  its meta parameter:
  
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  \macro<\numbering[indent=2,maxlndigits=3]{c}{n}>{                     │
  │ 2:  │      \measure<nn,wn,hn>{${n}}                                          │
  │ 3:  │      \hskip{${indent}}${n}:\hskip{                                     │
  │ 4:  │          \sub{${maxlndigits},${wn}}}\if{\unicode}{│  }${c}             │
  │ 5:  │  }                                                                     │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
  
  The macro is a callback  that expects two required  arguments. 𝐻𝑦𝑎δες calls this
  routine for every line of content passed to \𝑙𝑖𝑛𝑒𝑟𝑜𝑢𝑡𝑖𝑛𝑒, supplying the line co-
  ntent as the first parameter and the line index as the second.
  
  Since the line content is already  rendered when it is passed to the routine, it
  itself cannot be changed (e.g. using  \𝑡𝑒𝑥𝑡𝑏𝑓), it can only be laid out or deco-
  rated as a whole. The  \𝑛𝑢𝑚𝑏𝑒𝑟𝑖𝑛𝑔 routine, for instance, measures the line index
  in order to align the right gutter  border, and renders the line number, the bo-
  rder, and the content. The  \𝑓𝑎𝑛𝑐𝑦𝑙𝑖𝑠𝑡𝑖𝑛𝑔 macro then adds a frame around the co-
  ntent processed by the \𝑛𝑢𝑚𝑏𝑒𝑟𝑖𝑛𝑔 line routine.
  
  While using a line routine with a verbatim environment is certainly very useful,
  it is not  required. A line  routine can accept any regular 𝐻𝑦𝑎δες source, which
  will be processed and composed like any other source:
  
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  This is completely                                                    │
  │ 2:  │  fine too.                                                             │
  │ 3:  │                                                                        │
  │ 4:  │  …                                                                     │
  │ 5:  │                                                                        │
  │ 6:  │  We can have multi-line math here as well:                             │
  │ 7:  │                                                                        │
  │ 8:  │   ρ         ρ       ρ     ρ  λ     ρ  λ                                │
  │ 9:  │  𝑅     = ∂ Γ   − ∂ Γ   + Γ  Γ   − Γ  Γ                                 │
  │ 10: │    σμν    μ νσ    ν μσ    μλ νσ    νλ μσ                               │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
  
  
  𝐀𝐫𝐫𝐚𝐲𝐬
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  Variables can also hold arrays. Declare an array with the [] suffix:
  
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  \let<scores[]>{[90, 85, 72]}                                          │
  │ 2:  │                                                                        │
  │ 3:  │  First: \valueof<scores>[0]                                            │
  │ 4:  │  Second: \valueof<scores>[1]                                           │
  │ 5:  │  Length: \len<scores>                                                  │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
     ╭─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╮
  ╭──┴────────────╮                                                            │
  │ 𝐻𝑦𝑎δες Output │|··························································|│
  ╰──┬────────────╯                                                            │
     │   First: 90                                                            ░│
     │   Second: 85                                                           ░│
     │   Length: 3                                                            ░│
     ╰─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╯
  
  You can iterate over arrays with \𝑏𝑒𝑔𝑖𝑛{enumerate}:
  
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  \let<nums[]>{[10, 20, 30]}                                            │
  │ 2:  │                                                                        │
  │ 3:  │  \begin<nums>[i,val]{enumerate}                                        │
  │ 4:  │      Item ${i}: ${val} \\                                              │
  │ 5:  │  \end{enumerate}                                                       │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
     ╭─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╮
  ╭──┴────────────╮                                                            │
  │ 𝐻𝑦𝑎δες Output │|··························································|│
  ╰──┬────────────╯                                                            │
     │   Item 0: 10                                                           ░│
     │   Item 1: 20                                                           ░│
     │   Item 2: 30                                                           ░│
     ╰─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╯
  
  Arrays support stack and queue operations (\𝑝𝑢𝑠ℎ, \𝑝𝑜𝑝, \𝑒𝑛𝑞𝑢𝑒𝑢𝑒, \𝑑𝑒𝑞𝑢𝑒𝑢𝑒), and
  can be used in macros  for dynamic content  generation. For more  advanced array
  work – typed arrays,  computed access with  \𝑎𝑡/\𝑠𝑒𝑡, and map  collections – see
  the CL guide.
  
  
  𝐒𝐭𝐫𝐢𝐧𝐠 𝐎𝐩𝐞𝐫𝐚𝐭𝐢𝐨𝐧𝐬
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  Hyades provides basic string operations that are useful in macro conditionals:
  
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  \let<name>{Hyades}                                                    │
  │ 2:  │  \let<other>{TeX}                                                      │
  │ 3:  │                                                                        │
  │ 4:  │  \streq{${name},Hyades} \\ % 1 (equal)                                 │
  │ 5:  │  \streq{${name},${other}} \\ % 0 (not equal)                           │
  │ 6:  │  \strlen{${name}} \\ % 6                                               │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
     ╭─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╮
  ╭──┴────────────╮                                                            │
  │ 𝐻𝑦𝑎δες Output │|··························································|│
  ╰──┬────────────╯                                                            │
     │   1                                                                    ░│
     │   0                                                                    ░│
     │   6                                                                    ░│
     ╰─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╯
  
  The \𝑠𝑡𝑟𝑒𝑞 command compares two strings and returns 1 if they are equal, 0 othe-
  rwise. The  \𝑠𝑡𝑟𝑙𝑒𝑛 command returns  the length of a string.  Combined with \𝑖𝑓,
  these  let  macros branch on string  arguments – as we saw in the  \𝑏𝑜𝑜𝑠𝑡𝑦 macro
  above.

@label macro_guide
    \Titleframe{The Macro System}

    Hyades has two programmability systems -- a macro system aimed at typesetting
    convenience just like the macro system of TeX, and a general computational
    system (CL) aimed at efficient general purpose computation. This document
    describes the macro system. For CL and the Subnivean VM, see the
    \textit{Computational Lambdas \& Subnivean} guide.

    Think of macros as a smarter version of "search
    and replace" -- if Hyades finds a macro call, it will take the call arguments,
    find the macro definition, and literally replace the call site with the full
    macro body with argument references replaced. Since the macro body itself can
    call macros, this process is recursive until no more macros are found in the
    recursively expanded body, and only calls that remain are system primitives.
    After that the expanded body is processed by the normal parsing and rendering
    pipeline.

    \section{\textbf{Variables}}

    A variable is declared with \cmd{let}\<x\>\{value\}, and the value
    is accessed with \$\{x\}:

    \hylst{\verb|
\let<x>{123}
${x}|}
{%
    \indented {
        \let<x>{123}
        ${x}
    }
}

    Variables are \textit{polymorphic} -- they hold either integers or
    arbitrary rendered content. When used with numbers they support
    arithmetic; when used with content like \cmd{Boxed}\{abc\} they
    store and recall rendered output:

    \hylst{\verb|
\let<mybox>{\Boxed{Hello, World!}}
${mybox}|}
{%
    \indented {
        \let<mybox>{\Boxed{Hello, World!}}
        ${mybox}
    }
}

    When a variable holds an integer, it can be changed in place with
    mutating operations like \cmd{inc} (increment), or used as input to
    arithmetic, logic, and comparison commands. The numeric operations
    provided by Hyades are:

    \indented{\fancylist{
        - Incrementing:\quad \cmd{inc}\<x\>
        - Decrementing:\quad \cmd{dec}\<x\>
        - Adding:\quad \cmd{add}\{a,b\}
        - Subtracting:\quad \cmd{sub}\{a,b\}
        - Integer division:\quad \cmd{div}\{a,b\}
        - Multiplication:\quad \cmd{mul}\{a,b\}
        - Modulo:\quad \cmd{mod}\{a,b\}
        - Assignment:\quad \cmd{let}\<y\>\{\cmd{add}\{a,b\}\}
        - Equality:\quad \cmd{eq}\{\$\{x\},1\}
        - Non-equality:\quad \cmd{ne}\{\$\{x\},1\}
        - Less Than:\quad \cmd{lt}\{a,b\}
        - Less Or Equal Than:\quad \cmd{le}\{a,b\}
        - Greater Than:\quad \cmd{gt}\{a,b\}
        - Greater Or Equal Than:\quad \cmd{ge}\{a,b\}
    }}\vskip{1}

    An example:


    \hylst{\verb|
\let<x>{123}
\inc<x> \\ % 124
\inc<x> \\ % 125
\div{${x},5} \\ % 25
\mul{${x},${x}} \\ % 15625

\let<y>{\add{${x},${x}}}

${y} \\ % 250
\eq{${x},${y}} \\ 0
\ne{${x},${y}} \\ 1
\eq{${x},\sub{${y},${x}}}  \\ 1
|
    }{%
        \let<x>{123} \\
        \inc<x> \\
        \inc<x> \\
        \div{${x},5} \\
        \mul{${x},${x}}

        \let<y>{\add{${x},${x}}}

        ${y}\\
        \eq{${x},${y}}\\
        \ne{${x},${y}}\\
        \eq{${x},\sub{${y},${x}}}
    }

    \section{\textbf{Scoping Rules}}

    Variables are subject to simple scoping rules:

    \indented{\fancylist{
        - If the IDENTIFIER is all caps, it has a GLOBAL scope:

          \center{\tightframe{\verb|\let<MYGLOB>{123}|}}\vskip{1}

        - If the identifier is not all caps, it has a local scope:

          \center{\tightframe{\verb|\let<mylocal>{456}|}}\vskip{1}
    }}

    All declarations, access, and mutation of a GLOBAL variable will refer to a single
    storage location no matter where and when they're invoked; whereas local variables
    refer to one location \textbf{PER MACRO EXPANSION}.

    Let's explain this by example -- a common use of variables is counting
    chapters, sections, etc., so let's build a simple chapter macro that
    automatically increments chapter numbers. Start with a local variable:

    \hylst{%
       \verb|
\let<chapno>{0}

\macro<\chapter{title}>{%
    \inc<chapno>
    \culn[pad:2]{${chapno}.\quad ${title}}
}

\chapter{The Mask}
\chapter{The Yellow Sign}
|
    }{%
        \let<chapno>{0}

        \macro<\chapter{title}>{%
            \inc<chapno>
            \culn[pad:2]{${chapno}.\quad ${title}}
        }
{}

        \chapter{The Mask}
        \chapter{The Yellow Sign}
    }

    In the above example the local variable \textit{chapno} is not accessible to the
    \cmd{chapter} macro since the top-level document and each macro expansion use
    different hygienization scope (more on hygienization in advanced topics). The
    only way for the macro to access a local from a different hyg. scope is to know
    its hygienized name. This is achievable by passing the local as reference:

    \hylst{%
       \verb|
\macro<\chapterbyref[counter]{title}>{%
    \inc<${counter}>
    \culn[pad:2]{${${counter}}.\quad ${title}}
}

\chapterbyref[counter:\ref<chapno>]{The Mask}
\chapterbyref[counter:\ref<chapno>]{The Yellow Sign}
|
    }{%
    \vskip{0}
        \macro<\chapterbyref[counter]{title}>{%
            \inc<${counter}>
            \culn[pad:2]{${${counter}}.\quad ${title}}
        }

        \chapterbyref[counter:\ref<chapno>]{The Mask}
        \chapterbyref[counter:\ref<chapno>]{The Yellow Sign}
    }

    Here we pass \cmd{ref}\{chapno\} as an optional argument. If you just print out
    what the command produces, it's something like

    \center{_m0_chapno}

    which is the real key to the underlying storage. Globals don't undergo
    hygienization, so they are accessible with the variable names directly.
    Let's make use of that to write a cleaner chapter macro:

    \hylst{%
       \verb|
\let<CHAPNO>{0}
\macro<\chapterglobal{title}>{%
    \inc<CHAPNO>    
    \culn[pad:2]{${CHAPNO}.\quad ${title}}
}

% Some text here...

\chapterglobal{The Yellow Sign}

% Some text here...
|}{%
    \vskip{0}

    \let<CHAPNO>{0}
    \macro<\chapterglobal{title}>{%
        \inc<CHAPNO>    
        \culn[pad:2]{${CHAPNO}.\quad ${title}}
    }

    \chapterglobal{The Mask}

    Although I knew nothing of chemistry, I listened fascinated. He picked up an
    Easter lily which Genevieve had brought that morning from Notre Dame, and
    dropped it into the basin. Instantly the liquid lost its crystalline clearness.

    \chapterglobal{The Yellow Sign}

    There are so many things which are impossible to explain! Why should certain
    chords in music make me think of the brown and golden tints of autumn foliage?
    Why should the Mass of Sainte Cecile bend my thoughts wandering among caverns
    whose walls blaze with ragged masses of virgin silver? What was it in the roar
    and turmoil of Broadway at six o'clock that flashed before my eyes the picture
    of a still Breton forest where sunlight filtered through spring foliage and
    Sylvia bent, half curiously, half tenderly, over a small green lizard, murmuring:
    "To think that this also is a little ward of God!"

    }

    {}\\
    \section{\textbf{Conditional Evaluation}}

    The \cmd{if}-\cmd{else} construction lets you branch through multiple paths
    just like in other programming languages (and TeX). The syntax is a bit
    different though -- I didn't want to feel limited by the TeX grammar.

    The syntax is simple:

    \tightframe{\verb|\if{condition}{true branch}|}

    And optionally:

    \tightframe{\verb|\if{condition}{true branch}\else{false branch}|}

    The \cmd{condition} can be anything that evaluates to an integer, where:

    $$
        \fn{if}(cond) = \cases{
            \mathbf{TRUE} & \text{iff } cond\in\mathbb{Z}\setminus{0}, \\
            \mathbf{FALSE} & \text{iff } cond=0\text{.}
        }
    $$

    As an example, let's write a simple automatic grader that turns a name
    and a score into a row that also contains a calculated grade.

    The grader macro:

    \fancylisting{\verb|
\macro<\grade[name]{score}>{
    \row[frame:{b:single}]{
        \col{${name}}
        \col{${score}}
        \col{\if{\ge{${score},90}}{%
                    A%
                }\else{%
                    \if{\ge{${score},80}}{%
                        B%
                    }\else{F}%
                }
            }
    }
}|}

    \macro<\grade[name]{score}>{
        \row[frame:{b:single}]{
            \col{${name}}
            \col{${score}}
            \col{\if{\ge{${score},90}}{%
                        A%
                    }\else{%
                        \if{\ge{${score},80}}{%
                            B%
                        }\else{F}%
                    }
                }
        }
    }

    We can then use it to generate table rows like so:

    \hylst{\verb|
\center{
\table[width:20,pad:{l:1,r:1},frame:none]{
    \row[frame:{b:double}]{
        \col[align:r]{Student}
        \col[width:5,align:c]{\textpercent}
        \col[width:3,align:c]{}
    }
    \grade[Knuth D.]{100}
    \grade[Olsak P.]{89}
    \grade[Gates W.]{3}
}}
    |}{%
\center{
\table[width:20,pad:{l:1,r:1},frame:none]{
    \row[frame:{b:double}]{
        \col[align:r]{Student}
        \col[width:5,align:c]{\textpercent}
        \col[width:3,align:c]{}
    }
    \grade[Knuth D.]{100}
    \grade[Olsak P.]{89}
    \grade[Gates W.]{3}
}}
    }

    (The content of the table is a little nod to RNDr. Petr Olšák, my university algebra
    teacher who unknowingly got me into TeX.)

    Note that the \cmd{else} branch, if present, must
    occur \textit{immediately} after the closing bracket of the \cmd{if} branch, because we lack
    an "end" command. If the \cmd{else} command doesn't follow immediately, the conditional statement
    is fully completed and any further \cmd{else} won't be executed.

    {}\\
    \section{\textbf{Measure/Recall System}}

    The Measure/Recall System provides two key capabilities:

    \indented{\fancylist{
        - Capture content for further re-use\\
        - Measure the content for dynamic layout purposes
    }}

    The \cmd{measure} command measures the dimensions of the output rendered by its
    argument. It also stores the argument so it can be recalled later. Here is
    the full pipeline:

    \indented{\fancylist{
        - First, the content is virtually rendered in an infinite space, where it is measured
        - Then, the content is stored in the content registry
        - Three keys are returned to the user:
          - 1 key for the stored content, with which it can be recalled
          - 2 variable keys -- the width and the height
    }}

    \hylst{\verb|
\measure<c,w,h>{$\frac{\alpha}{\beta}+\gamma$}

\fancylist{
    - width: ${w}
    - height: ${h}
}

Content: ${c}
|}{%
\vskip{0}
    \measure<c,w,h>{$\frac{\alpha}{\beta}+\gamma$}

    \fancylist{
        - width: ${w}
        - height: ${h}
    }

    Content: ${c}
}

    This vastly increases the power of macros, which can do things like:

    \indented{\fancylist{
        - Fit stuff snugly into boxes
        - Render underlines that scale with the text they underline
        - Make responsive tabular layouts
        - Render code listings
    }}
    \vskip{1}

    \begin{hbox}
        \child[6]{\tightframe[0]{This}}
        \child[8]{\tightframe[0]{system}}
        \child[4]{\tightframe[0]{is}}
        \child[6]{\tightframe[0]{used}}
        \child[4]{\tightframe[0]{by}}
        \child[5]{\tightframe[0]{the}}
        \child[13]{\tightframe[0]{\cmd{tightframe}}}
        \child[8]{\tightframe[0]{\textit{stdlib}}}
        \child[7]{\tightframe[0]{macro}}
    \end{hbox}\\
    In fact the Measure/Recall system was first designed just to support this macro.

    \begin{didyouknow}
    \center{A SIMPLE UNDERLINE MACRO}
    Here's an example of a simple underline macro, which measures the content
    passed to it, then renders the content centered, and renders a centered
    horizontal rule under it using the measured width.

    \listing{
\verb|\macro<\myunderline{content}>{%
    \measure<c,w,h>{${content}}
    \center{%
        ${c}\\
        \center{\hrule[${w}]}
    }
}

\myunderline{Hey, this is underlined}
|}

    Many different underline macros are available in \hyades::stdlib -- feel free to
    explore it and create your own personal library. You're even encouraged to extend
    \hyades::stdlib and make a pull request to the repo!
    \end{didyouknow}

    {}\\
    \section{\textbf{Content Storage}}

    We saw that variables can hold rendered content. For content that you
    want to store and recall multiple times, \cmd{let} is the primary way:

    \hylst{\verb|
\let<mybox>{%
    \center{\Tightframe{This is my box.}}%
}

% Render it twice
${mybox}
${mybox}
|}{%
    \vskip{0}
    \let<mybox>{%
        \center{\Tightframe{This is my box.}}%
    }

    % Render it twice
    ${mybox}
    ${mybox}
}

    \begin{didyouknow}
    \center{LEGACY: ASSIGN/RECALL}
    The \cmd{assign}/\cmd{recall} pair is the original way to store and recall
    content. It still works and you'll see it in older code:

    \listing{
\verb|\assign<mybox>{\center{\Tightframe{stored}}}
\recall<mybox>|}

    For new code, prefer \cmd{let}\<name\>\{content\} and \textdollar\{name\}, which
    work uniformly for both integers and content.
    \end{didyouknow}

    {}\\
    \section{\textbf{MACROS}}

    Macros are the primary text-processing programmability feature in \hyades{}.
    As described in the introduction, they are a smart recursive find-replace --
    "smart" because they create their own variable scopes. Not everything prefixed
    with \textbackslash is a macro though, as there are several clades of
    \textbackslash:

    \indented{\fancylist{
        - Command
          - A \hyades{} kernel function whose execution and rendering are entirely
            defined in C. Some examples:
            - \cmd{macro}
            - \cmd{sqrt}
            - \cmd{textit}
        - System Macro
          - Is a macro that is \textit{translated} by the \hyades{} kernel to a macro that
            is then processed by the standard macro pipeline just like any other macro
          - This is required to handle syntax that the standard macro pipeline cannot parse.
            Some examples:
            - \cmd{list} is a system macro, because it uses a Markdown syntax to define the
              level of nesting of list items. Even though \hyades{} does have string processing
              primitives, lists require more powerful parsing than \hyades{} offers.
            - \cmd{table} is another example
        - \hyades{}::stdlib Macro
          - Macros written in \hyades{} itself (not C) that ship with \hyades{} by default.
            In practice, these live in the git repo in a big cassilda file
            ([stdlib.cld]), and during the build this file is used to generate C source where
            these macros exist as strings in a system macro registry. Some examples:
            - \cmd{fancylisting} uses a \textit{line routine} to wrap content in a box with a
              line number gutter
            - \cmd{center}, \cmd{hcenter}, \cmd{tightframe}, ...
        - User Macro
          - Macros defined by the user
          - Users can build their macro libraries and then \cmd{input} them into their documents
            and use them, or they can of course define them right in the document
    }}

    Let's take a look now at how the system macro \cmd{list} is expanded by the kernel:

    \hylst{\verb|
\diagnostics{expansion}
\diag_expand{
    \list{
        - First row
        - Nested row
        - Top-level again
    }
}
\printdiagnostics
|}{\verb|
\begin{vbox}
    \child{
        \begin{hbox}
        \child[1]{-}
        \child[1]{}
        \child[auto]{
            \linebreaker{raggedright}
            First row
            \linebreaker{greedy}
        }
        \end{hbox}
    }
    \child{
        \begin{hbox}
        \child[2]{}
        \child[1]{-}
        \child[1]{}
        \child[auto]{
            \linebreaker{raggedright}
            Nested row
            \linebreaker{greedy}
        }
        \end{hbox}
    }
    \child{
        \begin{hbox}
        \child[1]{-}
        \child[1]{}
        \child[auto]{
            \linebreaker{raggedright}
            Top-level again
            \linebreaker{greedy}
        }
        \end{hbox}
    }
\end{vbox}
|}

    You can use the \hyades{} diagnostic commands to inspect how any source looks when it
    is expanded. The \cmd{list} system macro above is expanded to layout primitives:

    \indented{\fancylist{%
        - 3 vertically stacked children (vbox)
        - Each child:
          - Is a horizontal stack (hbox)
          - Fixed-size empty child to render the level indent
          - 1-char-sized child to render the bullet
          - Autosized last child to render the line content using the remaining width
            - Content rendered ragged right (typographical term for left justification --
              since the content is not justified on both sides, the lack of space
              distribution on the lines makes the right edge of the paragraph appear
              ragged)
            - Linebreaker is reset to its original value
    }}

    That was the \cmd{list} system macro. The \cmd{fancylist} macro that is used throughout
    this document is, however, a ::stdlib macro -- a thin wrapper around \cmd{list} that customizes
    the bullet point appearance based on the rendering mode:

\fancylisting{\verb|
\macro<\fancylist[indent=2]{content}>{
  \assign<uni>{%
    \list[indent:${indent}, point1:●, point2:○, point3:○, ragged:1]%
      {${content}}}

  \assign<asc>{%
    \list[indent:${indent}, point1:-, point2:-, point3:-, ragged:1]%
      {${content}}}

  \if{\unicode}{\recall<uni>}\else{\recall<asc>}
}
|}

    The \cmd{unicode} command returns 0 if the content is being rendered in the ASCII mode
    (which is done by \cmd{setunicode}\{false\}) and 1 otherwise. The macro creates a content
    variable for both cases and then decides which one to recall. The unicode mode allows us
    to render nicer bullet points. It's a good practice to take \cmd{unicode} into account
    in macros when they potentially render non-ASCII output. During development I often
    wasn't disciplined enough to maintain this practice everywhere, so you might find math
    that produces unicode in either mode -- something I'm actively fixing.

    \fculn{Declaring}

    Let's learn how to write macros. A macro must start with the \cmd{macro} command, followed
    by a meta-argument (denoted by angle brackets) containing the signature -- basically a
    prescription of how the macro can be called. The meta brackets are followed by curly brackets
    with the macro body:

    \center{\tightframe{\verb|
\macro<\boosty[state=sleeping, indent]{text}>{%
    % we'll put the macro body here
}|}}

    This signature tells you:

    \indent{\fancylist{
        - The macro is called "boosty"
        - There are two optional parameters:
          - state: has a default string value "sleeping"
          - indent: has a default value of nothing
          - In general there can be 0 - N optional parameters
        - There is one primary (required) parameter "text"
          - We can have more 1 - N such parameters
        - We cannot define meta parameters
    }}

    \begin{didyouknow}
        \center{WHAT'S WITH THE \textpercent SIGN?}

        The real ones will know. The \textpercent is a comment character in both TeX and \hyades.
        As a text processing system, \hyades takes into account whitespace -- two newlines in
        a row means the end of the paragraph, etc. Inside a macro definition, if you put \textpercent
        at the end of the line, the newline itself is commented out. Consider the following example.

        \listing{
\verb|
\macro<\a>{
    Hey
}

\macro<\b>{%
    Hey
}

Some text
\a
Some text

More text
\b
more text
|}

    This produces:

        \listing{
\verb|
Some text

Hey Some text

More text Hey more text
|}

        The \cmd{a} macro doesn't consume the newline after \{, so when it is used between two lines
        of text, it expands into a newline and the text. The \textit{compositor} then sees two newlines
        in succession, which is an instruction to create a new paragraph. These trailing \textpercent
        are a well-known pattern in TeX.

    \end{didyouknow}


    All parameters can be accessed within the body using

    \center{\tightframe{\verb|${paramname}|}}

    Let's add some body to our macro:

\fancylisting{\verb0
\macro<\boosty[state=sleeping, indent]{text}>{%
    \assign<sleeping>{\verb#
  |\      _,,,---,,_
  /,`.-'`'    -.  ;-;;,_
 |,4-  ) )-,_. ,\ (  `'-'
'---''(_/--'  `-'\_)#}
    \assign<awake>{\verb#
_                ___       _.--.
\`.|\..----...-'`   `-._.-'_.-'`
/  ' `         ,       __.--'
)/' _/     \   `-_,   /
`-'" `"\_  ,_.-;_.-\_ ',
    _.-'_./   {_.'   ; /
   {_.-``-'         {_/#}

    \measureref<\ref<x>,\ref<width>,\ref<height>,\ref<awake>>
    \assign<textbox>{\frame[${width}]{${text}}}

    \let<is_sleeping>{\streq{${state},sleeping}}
    \let<is_awake>{\streq{${state},awake}}
    \let<known_state>{
        \add{% = OR
            ${is_sleeping},
            ${is_awake}}
    }

    \if{${known_state}}{%
        ${${state}} \\
        ${textbox}
    }\else{%
        $
        \text{Error: Boosty only has 2 states: }
        \cases{
            \text{sleeping} \\
            \text{awake}
        }
        $
    }
}
0}

    This macro also lives in ::stdlib as \cmd{boosty}, as a tribute to my cat,
    whose name is Boosty. :) By defining it again in our document, we override the
    ::stdlib macro. Let's unpack what it's doing:

    \indent{\fancylist{
        - \cmd{assign}
          - We define a content variable "sleeping" and we assign to it an ASCII
            art of a sleeping cat.
            - \cmd{verb} starts a \textit{verbatim environment}, which, just like in
              TeX, will render the enclosed text verbatim (no processing whatsoever)
              until the first occurrence of the terminating character that immediately follows the
              command (in our case it's "#" -- terminating character may be any
              non-letter character that doesn't occur in the verbatim content. The usual
              pick is "|", but our ASCII art already uses that).
          - Similarly we define an awake cat.
        - \cmd{measure}
          - We \cmd{measure} the width of the wider cat
            - \cmd{measureref} is a variant of \cmd{measure} which does not expand its
              arguments like \cmd{measure}, but instead accepts hygienized registry
              references (\cmd{ref}) and works directly on the registries, circumventing
              the standard pipeline. This exists mainly because of \cmd{verb}, which
              has a very complicated path through the standard pipeline and can sometimes
              produce non-obvious results when combined with other advanced features.
          - We create a content variable called "textbox", to which we assign the text
            that was passed in, and decorate it with a frame exactly the width we calculated
            above.
            - \cmd{frame} is a foundational framing macro that accepts many arguments, but
              here we only use it in its default form, which renders a single-line frame
              with sharp contents.
        - Parse parameters
          - We define two variables (is_sleeping and is_awake)
            - We initialize them with 0 or 1 based on whether the "state" parameter
              matches "sleeping" or "awake" via \cmd{streq}
            - Strings are passed without any special delimiters, because there
              is really no such thing as the string type in the macro system of \hyades{} --
              whatever value you pass in will just be physically placed wherever it is
              referred to with \textdollar\{value\}.
          - We define a helper variable called "known_state"
            - We assign to it the arithmetic analogy of the logical OR:
            - Addition
            - $0 + 0 = 0$ (false)
            - $0 + 1 = 1$ (true)
            - $1 + 0 = 1$ (true)
            - $1 + 1 = 1$ (true)
        - Rendering
          - If the state is known (i.e. either "sleeping" or "awake" -- strings that directly
            match the names of the content variables that we defined earlier), we will use
            indirection (\textdollar\{\textdollar\{x\}\}), fetch and render the associated ASCII art.
          - If it is not known, we will render an error message.
    }}

    \begin{didyouknow}
        \table[frame:single]{
            \row[frame:single, align:c]{
                \col[align:c]{Logical Operator}
                \col[align:c]{Arithmetic Equivalent}
            }
            \row{
                \col{$x\vee y\, (x \text{ OR } y)$}
                \col{$x+y$}
            }
            \row{
                \col{$x\wedge y\, (x \text{ AND } y)$}
                \col{$x\cdot y$}
            }
            \row{
                \col{$\neg x\, (\text{NOT } x)$}
                \col{$1-x$}
            }
            \row{
                \col{$x\oplus y\, (x \text{ XOR } y)$}
                \col{$x+y \mod{2}$}
            }
        }
    \end{didyouknow}

    \vskip{1}
    \fculn{Calling}

    A macro is called the same way it is defined. Optional arguments use named fields
    by default; positional syntax is not supported. Here are some calling conventions:

\fancylisting{
\verb|$\eval[to:2,from:1]{(x)}$ % Order doesn't matter.
$\eval[1, 2]{(x)}$ % DOES NOT WORK!

\columns[4]{left}{right}
\columns[pad:4]{left}{right}
\columns[pad=4]{left}{right} % Alternative syntax
\columns{left}{right} % Default employed

% Structured syntax for optional arguments
\concatadd[x:{a:4,b:3},y:{a:5,b:6}]
\concatadd[x:{a:4,b:3}]
\concatadd
|}
{}

    \macro<\underline{content}>{
        \begin{vbox}
            \child{${content}}
            \child{\hrule}
        \end{vbox}
    }

\begin{didyouknow}
    Any macro may be invoked using the LaTeX environment convention. Internally it is
    translated to a standard TeX call.

\listing{
\verb|\begin{center}
    Centered content
    $$ c^2 = a^2 + b^2 $$
\end{center}
|}

    This is true for any user macro, system macro, and Hyades command with the exception
    of \cmd{begin}\{hbox/vbox\}, which is a layout primitive that exists in the environment
    form natively and will not be translated to the TeX form.
\end{didyouknow}

{}

    \fculn{Line Routines}

    Line routines are an advanced feature inspired by TeX's output routines, except
    they work with lines, not pages. They allow you to post-process a rendered
    line using the full \hyades{} typesetting arsenal. Line routines were designed
    mainly for the code \cmd{listing} and \cmd{fancylisting} macros, allowing you to
    post-process verbatim content, frame it, and add a line number gutter.
    Let's look at the macro:

\fancylisting{
\verb|\macro<\fancylisting{c}>{
    \titleframe[pad:0]{\lineroutine<numbering>{${c}}}
}
|}

    A line routine is invoked by calling \cmd{lineroutine}\<r\>\{content\}. The command expects
    content in its required parameter, and a macro with a specific signature in its
    meta parameter:

\fancylisting{
\verb|\macro<\numbering[indent=2,maxlndigits=3]{c}{n}>{
    \measure<nn,wn,hn>{${n}}
    \hskip{${indent}}${n}:\hskip{
        \sub{${maxlndigits},${wn}}}\if{\unicode}{│  }${c}
}
|}

    The macro is a callback that expects two required arguments. \hyades{} calls this routine
    for every line of content passed to \cmd{lineroutine}, supplying the line content
    as the first parameter and the line index as the second.

    Since the line content is already rendered when it is passed to the routine, it itself cannot be
    changed (e.g. using \cmd{textbf}), it can only be laid out or decorated as a whole. The
    \cmd{numbering} routine, for instance, measures the line index in order to align the right
    gutter border, and renders the line number, the border, and the content. The \cmd{fancylisting}
    macro then adds a frame around the content processed by the \cmd{numbering} line routine.

    While using a line routine with a verbatim environment is certainly very useful, it is not
    required. A line routine can accept any regular \hyades{} source, which will be
    processed and composed like any other source:

    \fancylisting{
        This is completely\\
        fine too.

        ...

        We can have multi-line math here as well:

        $ R^\rho{}_{\sigma\mu\nu} = \partial_\mu\Gamma^\rho_{\nu\sigma} - \partial_\nu\Gamma^\rho_{\mu\sigma} + \Gamma^\rho_{\mu\lambda}\Gamma^\lambda_{\nu\sigma} - \Gamma^\rho_{\nu\lambda}\Gamma^\lambda_{\mu\sigma} $
    }

    {}\\
    \section{\textbf{Arrays}}

    Variables can also hold arrays. Declare an array with the \verb|[]| suffix:

    \hylst{\verb|
\let<scores[]>{[90, 85, 72]}

First: \valueof<scores>[0]
Second: \valueof<scores>[1]
Length: \len<scores>
|}{%
    \indented{
        \let<scores[]>{[90, 85, 72]}
        First: \valueof<scores>[0]\\
        Second: \valueof<scores>[1]\\
        Length: \len<scores>
    }
}

    You can iterate over arrays with \cmd{begin}\{enumerate\}:

    \hylst{\verb|
\let<nums[]>{[10, 20, 30]}

\begin<nums>[i,val]{enumerate}
    Item ${i}: ${val} \\
\end{enumerate}
|}{%
    \indented{
        \let<nums[]>{[10, 20, 30]}
        \begin<nums>[i,val]{enumerate}
            Item ${i}: ${val} \\
        \end{enumerate}
    }
}

    Arrays support stack and queue operations (\cmd{push}, \cmd{pop},
    \cmd{enqueue}, \cmd{dequeue}), and can be used in macros for
    dynamic content generation. For more advanced array work --
    typed arrays, computed access with \cmd{at}/\cmd{set}, and map
    collections -- see the CL guide.

    {}\\
    \section{\textbf{String Operations}}

    Hyades provides basic string operations that are useful in macro conditionals:

    \hylst{\verb|
\let<name>{Hyades}
\let<other>{TeX}

\streq{${name},Hyades} \\ % 1 (equal)
\streq{${name},${other}} \\ % 0 (not equal)
\strlen{${name}} \\ % 6
|}{%
    \indented{
        \let<name>{Hyades}
        \let<other>{TeX}
        \streq{${name},Hyades}\\
        \streq{${name},${other}}\\
        \strlen{${name}}
    }
}

    The \cmd{streq} command compares two strings and returns 1 if they are
    equal, 0 otherwise. The \cmd{strlen} command returns the length of a
    string. Combined with \cmd{if}, these let macros branch on string
    arguments -- as we saw in the \cmd{boosty} macro above.


@end

#target_prefix " "

#before_each
    \linebreaker{greedy}
    \setwidth{80}
    \setunicode{true}
    \setmathitalic{true}

    \macro<\indented{content}>{\indent[2]{${content}}}
    \macro<\cmd{x}>{\textbackslash{}\textit{${x}}}

    %%% Renders hy as source and rend as an example rendered output
    \macro<\hylst{hy}{rend}>{%
        \fancylisting{${hy}}

        \begin{vbox}
            \child{%
                \begin{hbox}
                    \child[3]{}
                    \child{\hrule{╭}{─}{╮}}
                    \child[2]{}
                \end{hbox}
            }
            \child{%
                \begin{hbox}
                    \child{
                        ╭──┴────────────╮
                    }
                    \child[1]{│}
                    \child[2]{}
                \end{hbox}
            }
            \child{%
                \begin{hbox}
                    \child[1]{│}
                    \child[1]{}
                    \child[15]{
                        \hyades{} Output │
                    }
                    \child{\hrule{|}{·}{|}}
                    \child[1]{│}
                    \child[2]{}
                \end{hbox}
            }
            \child{%
                \begin{hbox}
                    \child{
                        ╰──┬────────────╯
                    }
                    \child[1]{│}
                    \child[2]{}
                \end{hbox}
            }
            \child{%
                \begin{hbox}
                    \child[3]{}
                    \child[1]{\vrule[auto]{}{│}{}}
                    \child[1]{}
                    \child{${rend}}
                    \child[2]{}
                    \child[1]{\vrule[auto]{}{░}{}}
                    \child[1]{\vrule[auto]{}{│}{}}
                    \child[2]{}
                \end{hbox}
            }
            \child{
                \begin{hbox}
                    \child[3]{}
                    \child{\hrule{╰}{─}{╯}}
                    \child[2]{}
                \end{hbox}

            }
        \end{vbox}
    }

    \macro<\didyouknow{content}>{
        \vskip{1}
        \hcenter[60]{
        \hrule{}{.}{}
        ${content}
        \hrule{}{.}{}
        }
    }
#end
